rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: The type for Boolean properties, viz. properties that have only two possible values.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Boolean

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: An enumeration of the various categories of types, e.g. relationship, value type, abstract, primary entity, and enumeration. Note that only the categories of relationship, primary entity, and enumeration are currently used in the ontology.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Type Category

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Objects that are assigned this type are used in the conflation stage of the Satori pipeline.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Conflation Hint
rdf:Description.mso:type.type.deprecation_info: This type is not longer used in conflation. DeprecatedBy:[REDMOND\ianiles]

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Metadata representing date and time, as specific time points. It includes concepts like 'June 2013' and '7/10/1974 7:10:24 AM'.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Date/Time

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: The type for literals that store numeric values.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Decimal Number

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A grouping of types in the Satori Ontology, e.g. people, transportation, and tv.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Domain

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates a domain to its corresponding domain group, e.g. the Spaceflight domain is related to the Science domain group.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Domain Group

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A grouping of related domains. Although most domains in Satori are assigned a domain group, domain groups are currently not shown to the user.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Domain Group

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: An internal or external identifier for an element of the Satori Ontology
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Key

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates an internal or external identifier to the corresponding object in Satori.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Hash

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: The part of the key before the ":" that indicates the data source, e.g. "fb:", which stands for Freebase.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Namespace

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: The type for all namespaces, including namespaces for the Satori Ontology ("mso:"), as well as namespaces for type.object.key and type.object.subject_key (e.g. "fb:").
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Namespace

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: the most basic type in the system. This type contains all of the elements of the ontology, whether types, properties or entities.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Object

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: An abbreviated form of a name of the object. For example, the short name of Microsoft Office 2012 is Office 2012, the short name of the People's Republic of China is China, and the short name of the Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority is MARTA.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Short Name

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A value from 0 to 1 indicating the amount of adult content of the object. A score of 0 means that the object has no adult content.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Adult Score

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: An alternate name for the given object. Note that this property generally contains terms that would *not* be shown to a user, e.g. misspellings, ambiguous expressions, noncanonical phrases, etc.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Alias

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A description that contains markup, e.g. HTML or XML.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Annotated Description

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that points to information about a data provider of the given object.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: attribution

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: The preferred identifier for the object in a particular namespace, e.g. Satori, Facebook, Wikipedia, etc.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Best Key

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates an object to a concise or shortened form of a corresponding description.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Brief Description

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: The panoramas or photosynths to display for this entity.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Composite Image
rdf:Description.mso:type.property.deprecation_info: Use type.object.image and common.image.label to indicate that an image is a "composite image". DeprecatedBy:[REDMOND\ianiles] Successor:[mso:type.object.image]

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A virtual property that links an entity to another entity, when both are the subject of a particular text passage.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Coreferenced Entities

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A Boolean property that indicates whether the object exists or is of interest/importance at the present time, e.g. that a position is held. Note that the values of this property should be set as follows: type.object.current = 1: the object is of interest/importance at the present time. type.object.current = 0: the object was of interest/importance before the present time. In cases of future or unknown interest/importance, the property should not be set.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Current

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Text in the form of a definition or an exposition that specifies the most salient characteristics of the given entity.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Description

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property relating an entity to the most significant type(s) corresponding to the entity. For example, this property relates the Tom Hanks entity to the types mso:film.actor and mso:celebrities.celebrity.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Dominant Type

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates an entity to information about editorial updates that were made to the entity.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Editorial Record

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates an object to the etymology of the preferred name for the object.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Etymology

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A previous name for the object. Note that in, cases where an object has changed its name once and only once, the values for type.object.former_name and type.object.original_name will be the same. Otherwise, they may differ.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: former name

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property relating objects to their images. For historical reasons, type.object.preferred_image is semtantically identical with this field and should be preferred.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: image

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that links an object to a global identifier (i.e. an identifier that is independent of all of the sources from which information about the object is extracted) for the object in a particular namespace, e.g. Satori, Facebook, Wikipedia, etc.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Key

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A keyword, i.e. a search query or a search query term, associated with the entity.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Keyword
Locale
rdf:Description.mso:type.property.deprecation_info: It's not clear what the intended meaning of this property is. DeprecatedBy:[REDMOND\ianiles]

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates an entity to information about the translation of a name of the entity into another language/dialect.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Localization
Mention Url
rdf:Description.mso:type.property.deprecation_info: It's not clear what the intended meaning of this property is. DeprecatedBy:[REDMOND\ianiles]

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A word or phrase which refers to the object. Note that this field should contain only terms that can be displayed to a user.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Name

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: An affectionate name, usually based on a salient characteristic of the thing named, e.g. the nickname of John F. Kennedy was "Jack" and two nicknames of the city of Seattle are the "Emerald City" and the "Jet City".
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Nickname

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A Boolean property that indicates that the corresponding entity should not be conflated with other entities when this property is set to 1. When this property is not set (the default option) or is set to 0, the corresponding entity can be conflated with other entities.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Nonconflatable

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: The legal, formal, or full name for the object. For objects that that still exist (e.g. living people, existing countries), this will be the current official name. For objects that no longer exist, this will be the official name that the object had at the time of its demise (e.g. deceased people, former countries).
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Official Name

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: The name that the object had before any others, e.g. maiden name or the title of a movie when it was first released.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: original name

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Property relating an mso:type.object to another mso:type.object in which the entities are so closely related to be considered inter-changeable. An example is Amazon.com, Inc, the company, and amazon.com, the website. This property is based on an experimental property directly ingested from freebase.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Perceived Idential Entity

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Virtual property relating an entity to the mso:common.popularity relationship collecting data about the entity's popularity.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Popularity

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: The type.object.annotated_description that is regarded as the best one. The property type.object.annotated_description should be used for ingested sources, and the best descriptions will be promoted later to type.object.preferred_annotated_description.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Preferred Annotated Description

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: The type.object.description that is regarded as the best one. The property type.object.description should be used for ingested sources, and the best descriptions will be promoted later to type.object.preferred_description.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Preferred Description

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property relating an object to its best image(s). Note that the value for type.object.preferred_image should also be a value of type.object.image.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Preferred Image

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: The name of the object that is best for display purposes. Note that the value of type.object.preferred_name for a given object should also be a value of type.object.name
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Preferred Name

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that links an object to information about the ranking of the object.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Object Ranking
redirect
rdf:Description.mso:type.property.deprecation_info: It's not clear what the intended meaning of this property is. DeprecatedBy:[REDMOND\ianiles]

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates an object (type, property or entity) to a node in an external schema.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Related Concept

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates an object in the ontology (a type, property or entity) with information about a similar object in the ontology.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Related Object

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A virtual property that relates an object (type, property or entity) to information about its relationship to a node in an external schema.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Related External Object

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates an object to a limited set of source URLs that are considered to be representative for the object.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Representative Source URL

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that links an object to URLs that provide data for the object.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Source URL

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that links an object to a source-specific identifier for the object in a particular namespace, e.g. Satori, Facebook, Wikipedia, etc.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Subject Key

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Property relating an mso:type.object to its sub-types, sub-groupings that allow for more specificity in the description of instances. For example, the primary entity "fracture" would have as sub-types "wrist fracture" and "pathological fracture".
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Subtype

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Property relating an mso:type.object to its supertypes. These are the more general grouping for the type. For example, the primary entity 'yellow corn' would have a super type of 'corn'. 'Wrist fracture' would have a super-type of 'fracture'.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Supertype

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates an object to information about a block of text that denotes the object.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Text

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Property relating an mso:type.object to an mso:common.text value type that holds text regarding the entity. This property should be used when associating text passages that are not descriptions, in which case use type.object.description, or the text passages is not tokenized, in which case use type.object.tokenized_description.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Text Passage

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates an entity to a tokenized description of the entity. Note that this property should be used only when a description needs to be divided into tokens for some reason, e.g. to categorize phrases that make up the text. Otherwise, the property type.object.description should be used.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Tokenized Description

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A virtual property that relates an entity to a triple in which the entity appears as a subject.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Triple

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates an object to one of its types, e.g. it relates the entity for Tom Hanks to the type mso:people.person.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Type

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that links an object to a related webpage.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Webpage

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that links an object to the URL for a related webpage. Note that this is a virtual property defined on the property common.webpage.uri.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Webpage

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A relationship between two elements of the ontology, in most cases a relationship between an entity and another entity or a data value, e.g. type.object.name.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Property

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that links a deprecated property to information about when and why it was deprecated.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Deprecation Information

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Also known as the range of a property, it is the type from which all of the values of the property are taken.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Expected Type

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property for properties that represents the inverse of the current property. For example, if Bob is the parent of Jill, then Jill is the child of Bob. Thus, mso:people.person.children would have a type.property.inverse_of property to mso:people.person.parent.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Inverse of

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: The maximum number of values that a subject of the given property can be related to.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Maximum Cardinality

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: The minimum number of values that a subject of the given property can be related to.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Minimum Cardinality

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that is used to relate a given property to an instance of type.unit specifying the accuracy or exactness of the property. Among other things, the property type.property.precision is useful for determining when to conflate values of the given property. For example, the type.property.unit of commerce.consumer_product.age is type.unit.month. If we set type.property.precision for this same property to type.unit.month, it would mean that all measurements of product age that are in days, weeks, etc. can be rounded to the nearest month.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Precision of Property

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Property relating an mso:type.property to another property of which the former is a subproperty. This means that for cases in which 'specific_property subproperty broad_property' is true, then for any instance x, for which 'x specific_property y', then 'x broad_property y' is also true. This allows us to express more specific relationship between types while still inferring a broader relationship.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Subproperty

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Also known as the domain of a property, it is the type on which a property is defined and to which all of the subjects of the property must belong.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Type

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A unit of measure associated with the expected type of the property. For example, type.property.unit is set to type.unit.miles_per_gallon on the property automotive.automotive_class.highway_fuel_economy to indicate the unit of measure for its values.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Unit

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Type that is the collection of all Satori entities that should be published for consumption. This type allows for a general, high-level type that can be applied to any entity that needs publishing, but which may not have other MSO types in the category of 'primary entity'. Note this type has the category 'abstract'; it receives special handling in the entity platform.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Publishable Object

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A type containing any finite sequence of characters, i.e. letters, numerals, symbols and punctuation marks. Although there is no distinction between mso:type.string and mso:type.text in the ontology, these two types of literals are handled differently at the implementation layer. The type mso:type.string is language-independent, and the type mso:type.text is language-dependent. Examples of strings in this sense include URIs, identification keys, and any set of characters that is the same in any language.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Machine Readable String

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A type containing any finite sequence of characters, i.e. letters, numerals, symbols and punctuation marks. Although there is no distinction between mso:type.string and mso:type.text in the ontology, these two types of literals are handled differently at the implementation layer. The type mso:type.string is language-independent, and the type mso:type.text is language-dependent. Examples of text in this sense include any character string whose meaning may vary by language.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Text

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A type containing instances of properties. A triple consists of a subject (an entity, type or property), a property, and an object (an entity, type, property or literal), and it asserts that the subject is related to the object by the given property. For example, the triples <Paris, location.location.contained_by, France> and <Tale of Two Cities, book.written_work.author, Charles Dickens> mean, respectively, that Paris is contained within France and Charles Dickens is the author of the work ???Tale of Two Cities???.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Triple

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates a triple to its object or final argument. For example, France is the object of the triple <Paris, location.location.contained_by, France>.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Object

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates a triple to the property that links the subject and object of the triple. For example, location.location.contained_by is the property in the triple <Paris, location.location.contained_by, France>.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Property

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that specifies, in an informal way, the semantic relation between two entities in a triple. Note that the property should be used only when there is no relevant property in the ontology or when the relevant property is not known.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Relation

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates a triple to its object or final argument, when the final argument is a nonstandard value, e.g. a blob of text rather than an entity.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Relaxed Object

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that specifies the data source of the triple, e.g. Wikipedia, Freebase, IMDB, etc.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Source

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates a triple to its subject or first argument. For example, Paris is the subject of the triple <Paris, location.location.contained_by, France>.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Subject

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates a triple to a text passage from which the triple was extracted.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Text

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: the type of which all other types are instances.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Type

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates a type to the category of the type, e.g. primary entity, relationship, etc.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Category

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates a type to information about why the type is deprecated and what the successor of the type is.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Deprecation Information

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates a type to the domain of the type.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Domain

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates two types when we want to stipulate that no entities are permitted to belong to both of the types, e.g. mso:time.event and mso:event.agent or mso:people.person and mso:organization.organization. Note that this property should not be used in cases of "double identity", viz. cases where two distinct entities falling under two distinct concepts are referred to in the same way. This happens often with organizations and the locations that they occupy. For example, ???Stanford University??? is both a campus and an educational institution, but most people just refer to both entities with the same name. Another case is compositions versus tracks or singles featuring the compositions, particularly in popular music. These cases reflect a pervasive conceptual simplification that language users make, and it would be conterproductive to stipulate in the ontology that the types involved are exclusive.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Exclusive

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates a type to a subtype of the given type, when it is not possible for an entity to belong to the given type without also belonging to one of the subtypes specified by a mso:type.type.exhaustive assertion. For example, mso:sports.sports_agent has two subtypes: mso:sports.team and mso:sports.athlete. Since these two subtypes are related to mso:sports.agent via mso:type.type.exhaustive, every entity in mso:sports.agent is also in either mso:sports.team or mso:sports.athlete.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Exhaustive

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates a type to a base class of the type, i.e. it relates a type to another type from which it inherits properties. Note, however, that inclusion is not enforced and has no meaning with respect the instances in the entity graph.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Includes

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A precisely defined division of a physical quantity that is used as a standard for measurement of the same physical quantity.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Unit

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: The type for literals that reference an Internet resource.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: URI

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: The type that is the base class for all of the literals, e.g. Boolean, datetime, decimal, string, text, uri.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Value

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that is defined in terms of other properties. In many cases it will be either an inverse of a given property or the transitive closure of a set of properties.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Virtual Property
